	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Memblers</b> [ Fri Oct 23, 2009 12:50 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Here's the best description of the Famicom box - <a href="http://www.tripoint.org/kevtris/mappers/famicombox/index.html" class="postlink">http://www.tripoint.org/kevtris/mappers/famicombox/index.html</a>
<br />
<br />I made a partial schematic for a double-buffered CHR memory, it required 5 74HC573 chips and a 74HC245 for the data-bus (being bidirectional).  So a fully buffered cart may call for something similar to that.
<br />
<br />An EPROM emulator I use, with a ribbon cable/connector to replace a ROM chip uses 4 74HC590B chips between the RAM chip and the emulated ROM chip.  Using that had side-effects such as a partially glitched sprite-DMA, but but 300-ohm resistors in series with the data lines actually fixes that.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


